📖 Important Log Files

Ubuntu:

/var/log/syslog
/var/log/auth.log
/var/log/kern.log
/var/log/dpkg.log
/var/log/boot.log

Systemd Journal:

journalctl
🛠️ Task 1 – View System Logs
sudo journalctl

Latest 50 entries:

sudo journalctl -n 50

Follow logs live:

sudo journalctl -f

Current boot:

sudo journalctl -b

Previous boot:

sudo journalctl -b -1
🛠️ Task 2 – View Authentication Logs

Ubuntu:

sudo tail -50 /var/log/auth.log

Search failed logins:

grep "Failed" /var/log/auth.log
🛠️ Task 3 – Read Log Files

Last 20 lines:

tail -20 /var/log/syslog

First 20 lines:

head -20 /var/log/syslog

Interactive viewer:

less /var/log/syslog
🛠️ Task 4 – Search Logs

Search for "error":

grep -i error /var/log/syslog

Count errors:

grep -i error /var/log/syslog | wc -l

Search multiple patterns:

grep -Ei "error|failed|warning" /var/log/syslog
🛠️ Task 5 – Using awk

Show first column:

awk '{print $1}' /var/log/syslog | head

Print first three columns:

awk '{print $1,$2,$3}' /var/log/syslog | head
🛠️ Task 6 – Using sed

Display first 20 lines:

sed -n '1,20p' /var/log/syslog

Replace text (example):

echo "DevOps Engineer" | sed 's/Engineer/Architect/'
🛠️ Task 7 – Kernel Messages
dmesg

USB devices:

dmesg | grep -i usb

Errors:

dmesg | grep -i error
🛠️ Task 8 – Log Rotation

Check configuration:

cat /etc/logrotate.conf

View rules:

ls /etc/logrotate.d

Test rotation:

sudo logrotate -d /etc/logrotate.conf

Force rotation:

sudo logrotate -f /etc/logrotate.conf
